From cou.: 1 The redox chemistry of a newly synthesized small dendrimer containing six peripheral viologen units and a phosphazene core is described. The one-electron reduction of each viologen (total six electrons) leads to intermolecular dimerization of the reduced viologens borne by the same phosphorous atom, resulting in a color change from colourless to purple providing it with potential electrochromic applications.
From Soup: 1 The redox chemistry of a newly synthesized small dendrimer containing six peripheral viologen units and a phosphazene core is described. The one-electron reduction of each viologen (total six electrons) leads to intermolecular dimerization of the reduced viologens borne by the same phosphorous atom, resulting in a color change from colourless to purple providing it with potential electrochromic applications.
 ###### 
From cou.: 2 The growing evidence of climate change which is brought about by emissions of CO2 promoted by human activities has many predicted1 consequences associated with it, including drought, more violent storms, and deglaciation, to name just a few. The reduction of CO2 emissions has received serious attention from both the private and public sectors. One promising strategy towards this goal lies in improving the energy efficiency of current technologies that burn fossil fuels. Strikingly, energy consumption from buildings, and not transportation, is the greatest2 source of CO2 emissions. Increasing the heating and cooling efficiencies of buildings would have a significant positive impact on the environment.
From Soup: 2 The growing evidence of climate change which is brought about by emissions of CO 2 promoted by human activities has many predicted 1 consequences associated with it, including drought, more violent storms, and deglaciation, to name just a few. The reduction of CO 2 emissions has received serious attention from both the private and public sectors. One promising strategy towards this goal lies in improving the energy efficiency of current technologies that burn fossil fuels . Strikingly, energy consumption from buildings, and not transportation, is the greatest 2 source of CO 2 emissions. Increasing the heating and cooling efficiencies of buildings would have a significant positive impact on the environment.
