From cou.: 3 So-called smart windows based on electrochromic materials offer a promising way of regulating the amount of sunlight permitted to enter a building.3 Towards this end we have designed a viologen-based dendrimeric material that has under its reduced state significant absorption in the UV, visible, and near infrared regions (NIR) of the solar spectrum.
From Soup: 3 So-called smart windows based on electrochromic materials offer a promising way of regulating the amount of sunlight permitted to enter a building. 3 Towards this end we have designed a viologen-based dendrimeric material that has under its reduced state significant absorption in the UV, visible, and near infrared regions (NIR) of the solar spectrum.
 ###### 
From cou.: 4 The ability to prompt a fast and reversible movement of large amplitude in molecular bodies has appeared as a major scientific objective which is mainly driven by exciting foreseen applications in nanoscience. From this promising and highly competitive domain, a large number of nanometric small-scale mimics of macroscopic tools known as molecular machines,4 such as tweezers,5 gears,6 rotors,7 shuttles,8 muscles,9 and elevators10 that fulfill these requirements, have been designed to respond to various external stimuli, such as pH,11 redox change,12 temperature and light.13 We have employed these design principles in the synthesis and operation of our electrochromic material.
From Soup: 4 The ability to prompt a fast and reversible movement of large amplitude in molecular bodies has appeared as a major scientific objective which is mainly driven by exciting foreseen applications in nanoscience. From this promising and highly competitive domain, a large number of nanometric small-scale mimics of macroscopic tools known as molecular machines, 4 such as tweezers, 5 gears, 6 rotors, 7 shuttles, 8 muscles, 9 and elevators 10 that fulfill these requirements, have been designed to respond to various external stimuli, such as pH, 11 redox change, 12 temperature and light. 13 We have employed these design principles in the synthesis and operation of our electrochromic material.
 ###### 
From cou.: 5 Viologens, a class of compounds containing a 4,4′-bipyridinium dicationic core (BIPY2+), are well known for their rich redox chemistry, in particular the stable BIPY˙+ radical cation intermediate that is formed upon a one-electron reduction.14 In solution, BIPY˙+ displays an intense blue color as a result of a strong absorption band at ∼600 nm (ε605 ∼ 7500 M−1 cm−1 for methylviologen MV˙+ in MeCN15). For this reason, BIPY˙+ radical cations have been employed extensively as electrochromic materials.16 The ability of two BIPY˙+ radical cations to undergo dimerization15,17 is driven by radical–radical interactions mostly a consequence of pairing of the two spins into a singlet state. Upon dimerization, the absorption band at ∼600 nm is blue-shifted to ∼540 nm (purple color), while a significant absorption band at ∼870 nm (CT absorption) in the NIR region of the spectrum emerges. A large amount of research efforts have been directed towards enhancing the stability of these dimers in solution, including host–guest chemistry, mechanostereochemistry, and covalent preorganization.18 Radical cation π-dimerization, also known as “pimerization”,19 has been employed to generate a mechanical movement in the form of translation as well as rotation in mechanically interlocked molecules.20 Recently, Bucher et al. employed this pimerization to prepare a redox-activated rotating molecular carousel based on ferrocene and BIPY2+ units.21 The electrochromic properties of the BIPY˙+ dimer, however, have not been thoroughly investigated. Herein, we employ the strategy of covalent preorganization in a new phosphorus-based dendrimer (noted HV12+) containing six terminal BIPY2+ units homogeneously distributed on the periphery of the well-known hexatopic core, cyclotriphosphazene (CTP).
From Soup: 5 Viologens, a class of compounds containing a 4,4′-bipyridinium dicationic core ( BIPY 2+ ), are well known for their rich redox chemistry, in particular the stable BIPY˙ + radical cation intermediate that is formed upon a one-electron reduction. 14 In solution, BIPY˙ + displays an intense blue color as a result of a strong absorption band at ∼600 nm ( ε 605 ∼ 7500 M −1 cm −1 for methylviologen MV˙ + in MeCN 15 ). For this reason, BIPY˙ + radical cations have been employed extensively as electrochromic materials. 16 The ability of two BIPY˙ + radical cations to undergo dimerization 15,17 is driven by radical–radical interactions mostly a consequence of pairing of the two spins into a singlet state. Upon dimerization, the absorption band at ∼600 nm is blue-shifted to ∼540 nm (purple color), while a significant absorption band at ∼870 nm (CT absorption) in the NIR region of the spectrum emerges. A large amount of research efforts have been directed towards enhancing the stability of these dimers in solution, including host–guest chemistry, mechanostereochemistry, and covalent preorganization. 18 Radical cation π-dimerization, also known as “pimerization”, 19 has been employed to generate a mechanical movement in the form of translation as well as rotation in mechanically interlocked molecules. 20 Recently, Bucher et al . employed this pimerization to prepare a redox-activated rotating molecular carousel based on ferrocene and BIPY 2+ units. 21 The electrochromic properties of the BIPY˙ + dimer, however, have not been thoroughly investigated. Herein, we employ the strategy of covalent preorganization in a new phosphorus-based dendrimer (noted HV 12+ ) containing six terminal BIPY 2+ units homogeneously distributed on the periphery of the well-known hexatopic core, cyclotriphosphazene (CTP).
