From cou.: 10 We first examined the redox processes of BMV2+ as a control. BMV2+ is characterized by two reversible one-electron redox processes (E11/2 = −0.29 V, ΔE = 80 mV and E21/2 = −0.68 V, ΔE = 80 mV), while the CV voltammogram of hexaviologen dendrimer HV12+ can be interpreted by two reversible six electrons processes (E11/2 = −0.27 V, ΔE = 60 mV and E21/2 = −0.7 V, ΔE = 70 mV). The voltammetric wave of HV12+ has a shape that matches that of the corresponding molecule with a single electroactive center BMV2+, an observation consistent with the fact that the six identical and independent viologens within HV12+ are noninteracting electroactive centers.24a On the other hand, the difference in the magnitude of the peak-to-peak separation between BMV2+ and HV12+ (ΔE1/2 = 390 mV and 430 mV for the BMV2+ and HV12+, respectively) is an indication of the intramolecular dimerization occurring in HV12+.24c More precisely, BMV2+ compound exhibits two successive reversible reductions occurring at −0.33 and −0.72 V, generating the BMV˙+ radical cation and the fully reduced BMV0 neutral compound, respectively. Similarly, the CV of HV12+ reveals two reversible redox processes although slightly positively shifted for the first process at −0.30 V and slightly negatively shifted for the second process at −0.74 V. Chronocoulometric experiments (see ESI†) further demonstrate that the first reversible redox process of HV12+/HV6(˙+) involves six electrons, while that of BMV2+/BMV˙+ implies only one-electron transfer. It is well known that the thermodynamic stability of BIPY˙+ π-dimers induces positive shifts in the first redox-potential, while the second reduction processes leading to BIPY0 become negatively shifted.24b Square wave voltammetry (Fig. 1b) normalized to the ferrocene redox-couple further confirms the shifts of the first and second redox-potentials of HV12+ with respect to BMV2+. These shifts are much lower in magnitude, however, in comparison to the viologen dimers stabilized for example by CB[8],14f,24,25 or covalent preorganization, which is over 50 mV for both the first and second redox processes in each case. The relatively smaller shifts can be explained by the following mechanistic interpretation.
