From cou.: 37 Although the shifts in the redox potentials are small (E11/2 (BMV2+) − E11/2 (HV12+) = 40 mV, the fact that the number of electrons transferred is six still leads to large values of βDim. If one speculates about a system composed of only two BIPY˙+ units linked together covalently with a comparable value of βDim, one would expect the shift in the redox-potentials to be three times large. Previous reports showed that this is indeed the case.26 Digitally simulated CVs (see ESI†) based on this proposed mechanism match well with our experimental data. With eqn (6) in hand, we have now a means of evaluating βDim, which we have done in a variety of solvents (βDim = 1.3 × 104 in DMF, see Table S1 in the ESI†).
From Soup: 37 Only monotonous variation in the intensities of these absorption bands was observed as the concentration was increased ( Fig. 2a ), an indication that no significant amount of the intermolecular ( BMV˙ + ) 2 radical dimer is formed under our experimental conditions. On the other hand, the absorption spectra of HV D 6( ˙ +) reveal three prominent bands at 362, 540, and 870 nm, which are the characteristic of ( BIPY˙ + ) 2 radical dimers within the dendritic structure. In particular, the bands of the BIPY˙ + monomer at 395 and 600 nm shifted to shorter wavelengths upon dimerization, in addition to the appearance of a NIR band, which is most likely the result of a through space charge transfer transition. The λ max of these absorption bands remain unperturbed as the concentration is decreased ( Fig. 2b ), an observation that indicates the dimerization process is intramolecular ( β Dim = 7.32 × 10 7 M in MeCN, see Table S1 in ESI † ). Altogether, these results reveal that these materials will always absorb NIR radiation in the context of a smart window, regardless of the concentrations employed.
