From cou.: 39 Only monotonous variation in the intensities of these absorption bands was observed as the concentration was increased (Fig. 2a), an indication that no significant amount of the intermolecular (BMV˙+)2 radical dimer is formed under our experimental conditions. On the other hand, the absorption spectra of HVD6(˙+) reveal three prominent bands at 362, 540, and 870 nm, which are the characteristic of (BIPY˙+)2 radical dimers within the dendritic structure. In particular, the bands of the BIPY˙+ monomer at 395 and 600 nm shifted to shorter wavelengths upon dimerization, in addition to the appearance of a NIR band, which is most likely the result of a through space charge transfer transition. The λmax of these absorption bands remain unperturbed as the concentration is decreased (Fig. 2b), an observation that indicates the dimerization process is intramolecular (βDim = 7.32 × 107 M in MeCN, see Table S1 in ESI†). Altogether, these results reveal that these materials will always absorb NIR radiation in the context of a smart window, regardless of the concentrations employed.
From Soup: 39 This model system was fully optimized in its oxidized BV 4+ and reduced BV 2( ˙ +) forms. Structure optimizations performed in aqueous solution (IEFPCM model) 28 resulted in a molecular geometry where the two BIPY˙ + units are stacked in a nearly parallel fashion, with the angle between the two least-square planes defined by the BIPY˙ + units amounting to 3.1°, and up to six C⋯C distances in the range of 3.30–3.56 Å. A twist angle of ∼37° is obtained for its fully oxidized form, while two BIPY˙ + fragments show virtually no twisting about their 4,4′-C–C bonds. The diminution in the torsion angle is accompanied by a significant shortening of the 4,4′-C–C distance, which amounts to 1.474 and 1.426 Å in the BV 4+ and BV 2( ˙ +) systems, respectively. This is in line with recent crystallographic studies, in which small torsion angles in BIPY˙ + were considered as a signature of its radical cation nature. 15 Indeed, both SOMO and SOMO-1 in BV 2( ˙ +) show significant overlap (bonding character) between the 4,4′-ring carbon atoms of both BIPY˙ + units. An important delocalization of the SOMO and SOMO-1 ( Fig. 3 ) among the two BIPY˙ + units is also observed.
 ###### 
From cou.: 40 In order to gain insight into the nature of the pimerization process we have performed density functional theory calculations at the M06/6-31G(d,p) level,27 a computational approach that has been shown to provide good results for inclusion complexes of BIPY˙+ radical cations.15 Due to the large size of the system of interest, our calculations (Fig. 3) were performed on a simplified model denoted BV4+ where four of the six BMV2+ units of HV12+ were replaced by methyl groups.
From Soup: 40 As a proof of principle and in order to evaluate the potential of HV 12+ to serve as an electrochromic material, we constructed a device consisting of two transparent indium tin oxide (ITO) electrodes. A concentrated solution of 5.0 mM HV 12+ in 1 M NaCl in H 2 O was sandwiched between two ITO slides under nitrogen . The electrochemistry of the resulting device was investigated in open air employing one of the ITO slides as a working electrode, while the second ITO slide was used as the counter electrode as well as the reference electrode. Fig. 4 depicts the electrochemical properties of HV 12+ in the ITO device. The obtained cyclic voltammograms exhibit wave shapes typical for surface confined redox processes indicating adsorption of the compound onto the electrode surface. 29 The large peak-to-peak separation in the case of the ITO electrode is attributed to the high resistance of the electrode material. Moreover, the prepared device exhibited a reversible and relatively fast 30 color change (up to ten cycles without any significant changes, see ESI † ) from colorless to purple upon reduction as shown in Fig. 4 . The electrochromic property of the device was also examined by UV/Vis/NIR spectroscopy ( Fig. 4 ). Maintaining the voltage at −2 V resulted in absorption spectra similar to that obtained in solution. A large NIR band centred at 1123 nm as well as two absorption bands at 595 and 370 nm characteristic of the dimer formation were observed. The large intensity of the NIR band can be explained by the formation of aggregates on the surface of the ITO slides upon reduction .
 ###### 
From cou.: 41 This model system was fully optimized in its oxidized BV4+ and reduced BV2(˙+) forms. Structure optimizations performed in aqueous solution (IEFPCM model)28 resulted in a molecular geometry where the two BIPY˙+ units are stacked in a nearly parallel fashion, with the angle between the two least-square planes defined by the BIPY˙+ units amounting to 3.1°, and up to six C⋯C distances in the range of 3.30–3.56 Å. A twist angle of ∼37° is obtained for its fully oxidized form, while two BIPY˙+ fragments show virtually no twisting about their 4,4′-C–C bonds. The diminution in the torsion angle is accompanied by a significant shortening of the 4,4′-C–C distance, which amounts to 1.474 and 1.426 Å in the BV4+ and BV2(˙+) systems, respectively. This is in line with recent crystallographic studies, in which small torsion angles in BIPY˙+ were considered as a signature of its radical cation nature.15 Indeed, both SOMO and SOMO-1 in BV2(˙+) show significant overlap (bonding character) between the 4,4′-ring carbon atoms of both BIPY˙+ units. An important delocalization of the SOMO and SOMO-1 (Fig. 3) among the two BIPY˙+ units is also observed.
From Soup: 41 In summary we have synthesized a new phosphazene–viologen dendrimer ( HV 12+ ) and studied its switching and electrochromic properties. Although dimerization of the viologens is typically hampered in organic solvents (unless at low temperature, or high concentration), the preorganization of the designed dendrimer allows efficient intramolecular dimerization of the two viologens borne by the same phosphorous atom in a wide range of solvents upon reduction leading to a reversible color change (colorless to purple), which was assessed through spectroscopic and electrochemical experiments and supported by theoretical analysis. Taking advantage of its electrochemical properties, i.e. showing a change in the absorption spectrum of HV 12+ by providing external stimuli in the form of electrons, this molecule has been tested for smart window application which was successfully verified through an initial set of experiments. Its ability to absorb in both the UV/Vis and the NIR regions has the potential to limit the heat entering a building and therefore economize energy consumption.
 ###### 
From cou.: 42 As a proof of principle and in order to evaluate the potential of HV12+ to serve as an electrochromic material, we constructed a device consisting of two transparent indium tin oxide (ITO) electrodes. A concentrated solution of 5.0 mM HV12+ in 1 M NaCl in H2O was sandwiched between two ITO slides under nitrogen. The electrochemistry of the resulting device was investigated in open air employing one of the ITO slides as a working electrode, while the second ITO slide was used as the counter electrode as well as the reference electrode. Fig. 4 depicts the electrochemical properties of HV12+ in the ITO device. The obtained cyclic voltammograms exhibit wave shapes typical for surface confined redox processes indicating adsorption of the compound onto the electrode surface.29 The large peak-to-peak separation in the case of the ITO electrode is attributed to the high resistance of the electrode material. Moreover, the prepared device exhibited a reversible and relatively fast30 color change (up to ten cycles without any significant changes, see ESI†) from colorless to purple upon reduction as shown in Fig. 4. The electrochromic property of the device was also examined by UV/Vis/NIR spectroscopy (Fig. 4). Maintaining the voltage at −2 V resulted in absorption spectra similar to that obtained in solution. A large NIR band centred at 1123 nm as well as two absorption bands at 595 and 370 nm characteristic of the dimer formation were observed. The large intensity of the NIR band can be explained by the formation of aggregates on the surface of the ITO slides upon reduction.
