From cou.: 43 In summary we have synthesized a new phosphazene–viologen dendrimer (HV12+) and studied its switching and electrochromic properties. Although dimerization of the viologens is typically hampered in organic solvents (unless at low temperature, or high concentration), the preorganization of the designed dendrimer allows efficient intramolecular dimerization of the two viologens borne by the same phosphorous atom in a wide range of solvents upon reduction leading to a reversible color change (colorless to purple), which was assessed through spectroscopic and electrochemical experiments and supported by theoretical analysis. Taking advantage of its electrochemical properties, i.e. showing a change in the absorption spectrum of HV12+ by providing external stimuli in the form of electrons, this molecule has been tested for smart window application which was successfully verified through an initial set of experiments. Its ability to absorb in both the UV/Vis and the NIR regions has the potential to limit the heat entering a building and therefore economize energy consumption.
